Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Awajun (Aguaruna) are an indigenous people of the Peruvian
jungle. Historically, they lived primarily on the banks of the
Maranon River, a tributary of the Amazon in northern Peru near the
border with Ecuador. Currently, they possess titled community lands
in 4 of Peru's regions: Amazonas, Cajamarca, Loreto, and San Martin.
According to Peru's 1993 Census the Aguaruna (Awajun) numbered
approximately 45 000. World Census data for 2000 lists their
population at just over 38 000 <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aguaruna>.

It is estimated now that approximately 3500 people have been bitten
by vampire bats and the number of deaths has risen to at least 20,
which includes 5 children between the ages of 5 and 10 years. Another
3 children are suspected to have died as a result of rabies virus
infection, but this cannot be confirmed. Hopefully the use of
mosquito netting to provide protection against bats at night combined
with the developing vaccination campaign will help to stem this
outbreak which is several months old.

A map showing the location of the Amazonas region in northern Peru
can be accessed at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/peru.pdf>. The
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Peru can be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/r/00Dq>. - Mod.CP]
